discussion between necros. Fact is, do whatever you feel comfortable with. From my own experience, aggro kiting seems to cost me less mana (since it utilizes our free ~40dps dot AKA boner), but each to his own and if root-cook works for you, then do that :-)<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="Verdana" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Also, I have grouped enough times in HoH basements to know even the best 65 monks/sks have hard time breaking some of these pairs. And when a sentry pops, I doubt the average necro could manage to do it.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I don't know what kind of monks/SKs you've been grouped with, but it's never been a problem to me. The theoretical hardest possible scenario is if all spawns are sentries, so you can't use snare to split. Still, it's not all that hard. Cast on one (non-dot spell, since it's not always the mob you cast on which stays a bit longer before pathing back), two will come, FD, ususally one will path back and reset before the other, when this happens, get up, dot the remaining one, and only he will come. I've had to do this a couple of times now when 2 sentries are next to eachother, but I really fail to see how a monk who is flagged for HoH can't pull this off. The scenario with 1 sentry and 1 guard/guardian is so easy it's not even funny. Just snare the guard/guardian, fd, wait for spawn to reset, get up and snared one will come for you.<br /><br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=461830" target="_blank"><b>Graar Raar</b></a> -Arch lich of Venril Sathir<br />" Skeley form whistles in the wind and makes NPCs want to punch you in the pancreas!" - Tao</span></font></td>
